AB  - This study investigates the utility of a thought-listing procedure for measuring racial attitudes based on the logic of a partially structured measure. Two studies are conducted to explore this possibility. Two episodes of Law and Order are used as the stimuli to replicate the findings. Both convergent and discriminant validity are tested. Results indicate that the partially structured measure has no significant relation with either explicit or implicit measures of racial attitudes. Implications of the findings are discussed, such as the existence of aversive racism, and the validity of the partially structured measure to detect people's racial attitudes. Adapted from the source document.
